"""
MKT Christ Commentary — John chapter 7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-john-7-7.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/echoes/john.json (OT connections already documented)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/john.json (chs 1–4 for terminology carry-forward)

Key decisions in this range:
- Author referred to as "the Evangelist" (consistent with chs 1–4)
- "Christ" used for Messianic identity; "Jesus" in narrative-level descriptions
- Directness levels stated in prose: "A type:", "A shadow:", "A fulfillment:", "A direct:", "A revelation of God:"
- v2 (Tabernacles): classified as type/shadow — the feast's water-pouring ceremony is the backdrop for vv.37-39
- v14 (teaching in the temple): fulfillment of Mal 3:1 — the Lord comes suddenly to his temple
- v16-18 (divine authority of teaching): fulfillment of Deut 18:18 — the prophet whose words are God's words
- v27 (messianic hiddenness): the crowd's tradition is correct in a deeper sense than they know — Christ's
  heavenly origin is indeed hidden from them
- v28 ἐγώ εἰμι: carries the divine-name echo (Exod 3:14) as in 4:26, though not the bare construction
- v37-38 (living water): direct fulfillment of Isa 55:1, Zech 14:8, Ezek 47:1-9; the ambiguity of "him"
  (believer or Christ as the source) is noted and the Christ-as-temple reading is defended
- v39 (Spirit after glorification): fulfillment of Joel 2:28-29, Ezek 36:26-27
- v40 (the Prophet): correct identification per Deut 18:15 but insufficient — he is more
- v41-42 (Bethlehem objection): Johannine irony — the scriptural objection is unwittingly an argument for Jesus
- v43 (division): classified as revelation of God — Christ is the eschatological stone of stumbling (Isa 8:14)
- Brief entries for narrative transitions; density proportional to Christological freight
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN = {
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>A shadow: the Jewish leaders seeking to kill Jesus fulfills the pattern of the rejected prophet who speaks God\'s word into a hostile covenant community. The Evangelist has already aligned Jesus with the Servant of Psalm 69 (hated without cause) and with Jeremiah, whose temple proclamation brought a death warrant from the priests. Jesus\'s strategic avoidance of Judea is not fear but the measured movement of the one whose hour is not yet determined by human violence — only by divine appointment.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A type: the Feast of Tabernacles (Sukkot) is the liturgical frame for the entire chapter, and its structure is Christologically dense. The feast commemorated Israel\'s wilderness wandering and God\'s provision of water from the rock (Exod 17:6; Num 20:8); it also anticipated, in Zechariah\'s eschatological vision (Zech 14:16–19), the gathering of all nations to Jerusalem in the final age. The water-pouring ceremony on each of the seven days — priests drawing water from the Siloam pool and pouring it on the altar — was the backdrop against which Jesus\'s proclamation in vv.37–38 would land. The Evangelist places Christ at the feast not incidentally but as the fulfillment the feast was designed to foreshadow.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus\'s brothers urge public self-display — "show yourself to the world" — which is precisely what the Incarnation is, but on terms set by the Father rather than family pressure. The demand echoes the wilderness temptation\'s logic (demonstrate, prove, make yourself known on your own schedule). The Evangelist positions this against the pattern of Psalm 69:8: "I am a stranger to my brothers." The Son who came to save the world is first a stranger within his own household.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "no one who wants to become a public figure acts in secret" states the logic of worldly visibility — but Jesus operates by an entirely different economy. He will make himself known to the world, but through the cross rather than spectacle. The irony the Evangelist intends is that the full disclosure of who Jesus is — the most public act in human history — will occur at the moment of maximum apparent shame.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A shadow: the unbelief of Jesus\'s own brothers enacts the Isaianic Servant pattern with precision. Isaiah 53:3 describes the Servant as "despised and rejected" — and this rejection begins within his own family. The Evangelist\'s editorial comment ("for even his own brothers did not believe in him") is not an incidental biographical note but a Christological marker: the one who came to his own and was not received (1:11) experiences that rejection first in his own household.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "my time is not yet here" (<em>ho kairos ho emos</em> — my appointed season) establishes the governing principle of Jesus\'s movements throughout the chapter. The Greek <em>kairos</em> is not merely calendar time but the divinely appointed moment — the term the prophets used for God\'s decisive interventions (Hab 2:3: "the revelation awaits an appointed time"). Christ\'s entire mission operates within a schedule set before his incarnation, and no pressure — familial or official — can accelerate it.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "it hates me because I testify that its works are evil" defines the structural reason for the world\'s hostility toward Christ. The Evangelist draws on the Psalm 69 pattern (the psalmist hated without cause) and on Amos 5:10 (those who hate the one who upholds justice). Christ\'s presence is itself a testimony — the light that exposes darkness (3:19–20) — and the world\'s hatred is a response to that exposure, not to any provocation he manufactures.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: the reiteration of "my time has not yet fully come" reinforces the divine sovereignty over Jesus\'s timeline. His apparent absence from the feast, followed by his secret arrival (v.10), mirrors the pattern of divine hiddenness before the decisive theophany — God who conceals before he reveals. The entire Johannine narrative is calibrated to a schedule whose end-point is the cross; every prior movement is preliminary.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus remains in Galilee, unmoved by family expectation. The Evangelist uses the deliberate pacing of the narrative to underscore that Christ acts from the Father\'s timing alone. Every delay in the Gospel of John (cf. the delay before Lazarus, 11:6) serves the same theological function: the apparent slowness is divine orchestration, not hesitation.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A shadow: Jesus goes up to the feast "not publicly, but in secret" — the pattern of the concealed Servant (Isa 49:2: "he made me into a polished arrow and concealed me in his quiver"). The self-concealment is not evasion but strategy: the hour of public disclosure will come, and it will not be at a festival entry but at a cross. The Evangelist\'s irony is that the one who is the world\'s light enters the feast in darkness.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: the leaders\' search for Jesus at the feast — "Where is he?" — is the reverse image of the seeking that will characterize his opponents after his departure: "You will look for me but you will not find me" (v.34). The present seeking is hostile; the future seeking will be desperate and fruitless. Both are judgments on those who encounter Christ without recognizing who he is.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: the divided crowd response — "a good man" versus "he deceives the people" — enacts the Isaianic Servant pattern with precision: "he was despised, and we held him in low esteem" (Isa 53:3). The accusation of deception is the charge that Deuteronomy 13:5 attaches to the false prophet who leads Israel astray — its application to Jesus is the Evangelist\'s most pointed irony, since the one accused of deception is the one who defines himself as the truth (14:6).</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: the suppression of public testimony about Jesus — "for fear of the leaders" — shows the distortion of witness that Christ\'s presence provokes in a world where truth is subordinated to social power. The silence itself is a kind of testimony in negative: the leaders\' authority depends on keeping Christ\'s claims from public discussion. Isaiah 59:14–15 describes a state where truth stumbles in the public square; the Evangelist shows this operating in real time.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A fulfillment: Malachi 3:1 promised that the Lord would "suddenly come to his temple" — the one who was being sought would arrive where he was expected. Jesus\'s appearance in the temple courts halfway through the feast fulfills this pattern. His teaching there is not merely instructional but an act of divine presence: the one to whom the temple pointed takes up his position within it and begins to expound the things of God with an authority the temple establishment does not possess.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A fulfillment: "How does this man know letters without having been taught?" echoes Isaiah 50:4: "The Sovereign LORD has given me a well-instructed tongue... morning by morning he wakens, he wakens my ear to listen." The Servant\'s learning is directly from God, bypassing normal human channels. The leaders\' amazement is the inverse recognition of this: they cannot account for Jesus\'s authority within their own categories of scribal training, because his authority does not come from that system.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A fulfillment: "My teaching is not my own — it comes from the one who sent me" directly instantiates the promise of Deuteronomy 18:18: "I will put my words in his mouth, and he will tell them everything I command him." The prophet like Moses was identified precisely by this characteristic — he speaks God\'s words, not his own. Jesus here identifies himself as that prophet, not by claiming the title but by describing the relationship that the title pointed to.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: the epistemological criterion Jesus offers — willingness to do God\'s will as the condition for recognizing divine teaching — discloses the pattern by which the Spirit works in those who will later receive him (v.39). The receptivity to Christ\'s teaching is not intellectual assent but moral orientation: those who are turned toward God\'s will can recognize God\'s word when they hear it. This is the positive counterpart to the world\'s hatred (v.7): those oriented toward God recognize Christ; those oriented toward themselves do not.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: the selfless orientation toward the sender\'s glory is Jesus\'s self-authentication as the genuine sent one. Numbers 16:28 records Moses\'s vindication formula — "this is how you will know the LORD has sent me" — grounded in his lack of personal agenda. Jesus applies the same logic: he who seeks the glory of the one who sent him is true; the absence of self-seeking is the mark of divine commission. Christ is the fulfillment of every genuinely sent messenger Israel\'s history anticipated.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A revelation of God: "Has not Moses given you the law? Yet not one of you keeps the law" — Christ turns the law against those who claim to enforce it and thereby exposes the inadequacy of Torah-observance as the path to life. The law was given through Moses; but Moses himself anticipated a greater prophet whose words would be the definitive word of God (Deut 18:15). The law\'s function in the hands of its custodians has been inverted: rather than directing them toward the one it anticipates, it has become a weapon against him.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: the charge "you have a demon" leveled at Jesus for claiming someone seeks to kill him is the same accusation that will be escalated in chapter 8. The pattern of the rejected witness being dismissed as disordered or dangerous recurs throughout the Servant Songs: Isaiah 53:4 — "we considered him stricken by God, smitten by him." The crowd\'s dismissal is a form of the low esteem in which the Servant was held.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "I did one miracle, and you are all amazed" refers to the Sabbath healing of chapter 5. That single sign has generated the controversy animating the entire chapter. Christ\'s signs are not self-promotion but revelatory acts — each one disclosing something about his identity that the authorities cannot integrate into their existing framework. The Evangelist\'s irony is that the sign which astonishes them is simultaneously the evidence of who he is.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A shadow: the argument that Moses gave circumcision (though the patriarchs established it — Gen 17:12) and circumcision is performed on the Sabbath without violating Torah reveals Jesus engaging in rabbinic qal wa-homer (lighter-to-heavier) reasoning. The deeper point is Christological: the entire covenant structure that circumcision encoded — membership in the people of God, covenant identity — finds its fulfillment in Christ, the one in whom circumcision of the heart (Deut 30:6; Jer 4:4) becomes possible.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "if a boy can be circumcised on the Sabbath so that the law of Moses may not be broken, why are you angry with me for healing a man\'s whole body?" — the argument from circumcision (affecting one member) to whole-body healing (a greater act) follows a logic Jesus applies to himself. He is not breaking the Sabbath but fulfilling what the Sabbath pointed toward: the rest that comes from the wholeness God gives. Healing is a Sabbath act precisely because it anticipates the eschatological rest.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A revelation of God: "stop judging by appearances; judge with right judgment" applies Isaiah 11:3–4 to the present situation. The messianic king was prophesied to judge not by what his eyes see or his ears hear but with righteousness and justice. Jesus is calling for the very discernment that Isaiah associated with the Messiah — and in doing so, implicitly inviting recognition: the one who speaks this way is the one Isaiah described.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: the Jerusalem crowd\'s astonishment — "Isn\'t this the man they seek to kill? Here he is speaking openly!" — is the Evangelist\'s way of showing the irresistible public character of Christ\'s ministry. He cannot be silenced. Jeremiah\'s temple speech (Jer 26:8–11) brought a death sentence that was not carried out; the pattern repeats: those who speak God\'s word in the temple courtyard attract death threats but divine protection.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: "Have the authorities really concluded that he is the Messiah?" — the question is asked ironically (the authorities have not concluded this), but the Evangelist intends it as a genuine question the reader should answer. Genesis 49:10 promised that Judah\'s ruler would come; the crowd is asking, without knowing they are asking, whether the fulfillment of that promise stands before them. The answer the narrative will provide is yes.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "when the Messiah comes, no one will know where he is from" reflects a Second Temple tradition about messianic hiddenness. The crowd\'s argument against Jesus — "we know where this man is from" — is correct at one level (he is from Nazareth in Galilee) but wrong at the level that matters: his true origin is the Father who sent him (v.29), and this is genuinely unknown to them. The crowd\'s objection inadvertently witnesses to Christ\'s heavenly origin — the source that is, indeed, hidden from all who do not know the Father.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A direct revelation: Jesus\'s cry in the temple — "Yes, you know me, and you know where I am from; I have not come on my own authority, but he who sent me is true, whom you do not know" — uses the <em>egō eimi</em> construction with the Exod 3:14 register (as in 4:26; 6:35). The concession ("you know me, you know where I am from") is ironic: they know the surface of his origin but not the depth. The one who sent him is the one they do not know — the God they claim to worship (8:54–55). The Incarnation is hidden even to those who see it.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "But I know him, because I am from him and he sent me" is the Prologue\'s claim (1:1–2, 14) restated as testimony in a controversy. The pre-existent relationship between the Son and the Father — not mere proximity to God but origination from him — is the ground of Jesus\'s unique knowledge and authority. Isaiah 49:1 describes the Servant called from the womb; Jesus traces his origin further back than birth.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: the inability of the crowd to lay hands on Jesus — "because his hour had not yet come" — is the Evangelist\'s recurring signature of divine sovereignty over the Passion timeline. The hour (<em>hōra</em>) of Christ\'s glorification/death is a fixed point in divine planning (Ps 31:15: "my times are in your hands"). Every failed attempt to arrest or kill Jesus before the appointed moment is not a narrative accident but a theological statement: the cross happens when God wills it, not when his enemies can arrange it.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "When the Messiah comes, will he perform more signs than this man?" — the crowd\'s reasoning from signs to messianic identity is the Evangelist\'s way of showing Isaiah 35:5–6 at work. The signs of the messianic age (blind seeing, deaf hearing, lame walking) have been appearing; many draw the correct inference. The irony is that the question is rhetorical for those who ask it but the Evangelist intends a definitive answer: no.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: the official decision to arrest Jesus is the institutional response to Christ\'s signs generating belief. The chief priests and Pharisees send temple guards — not for theological debate but for physical removal. The pattern of Jeremiah 20:1–2 (the priest Pashur having Jeremiah beaten for his temple prophecy) is being replicated; the authorized religious structure mobilizes against the one speaking God\'s words in God\'s house.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "I am with you for only a short time, and then I am going to the one who sent me" — Jesus speaks from the perspective of the entire arc of his mission, including cross and ascension. His presence among them is a temporally bounded gift; its ending is not abandonment but return to the Father. Isaiah 55:6 — "seek the LORD while he may be found" — provides the register: there is an appointed time for finding; after that, the seeking will not avail.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "you will look for me but you will not find me; where I am, you cannot come" — the future failed seeking is a form of judgment on those who rejected Christ while he was present. Proverbs 1:28 (wisdom\'s warning: "then they will call to me but I will not answer") and Hosea 5:15 (God returning to his place until Israel bears its guilt) both inform this pronouncement. Christ embodies wisdom and the divine presence; his departure renders the usual human strategies of seeking fruitless.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: the leaders\' speculative misunderstanding — "will he go teach the Greeks?" — is the Evangelist\'s deepest irony in the chapter. They speak better than they know. The mission to the Gentile world (the "dispersed among the Greeks") is precisely what Christ\'s departure will set in motion; the book of Acts narrates its fulfillment. Isaiah 49:6 (the Servant as a light to the Gentiles) and Isaiah 11:10–12 (the nations streaming to the root of Jesse) are the OT texts that this ironic prophecy actualizes.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A theme: the leaders repeat the saying they cannot interpret: "where I am, you cannot come." Their inability to understand it is the Evangelist\'s way of showing that access to Christ — including knowledge of where he is going — requires the Spirit (16:12–15). Deuteronomy 4:29 promised that seeking God with the whole heart would result in finding; the leaders seek Jesus, but not on the terms that make finding possible.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct fulfillment: on the last day of the feast — when the water-pouring ceremony culminated and the liturgical enactment of God\'s wilderness provision reached its annual climax — Jesus stands and cries out: "If anyone is thirsty, let him come to me and drink." The cry directly fulfills Isaiah 55:1 ("come, all you who are thirsty, come to the waters") and Zechariah 14:8 (on the eschatological day, living water will flow from Jerusalem). The feast\'s enacted promise of water is now present in person. Christ does not describe the water of the age to come — he announces that he is it.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "rivers of living water will flow from within him" — the "him" is deliberately ambiguous in the Greek, and the most defensible reading is that Christ is the source (the temple from which the eschatological river flows, Ezek 47:1–9), with the believer as the channel through whom it reaches others. The scripture Jesus cites is not a single verse but a composite of the OT water imagery: Isaiah 44:3 (the Spirit poured out like water), Ezekiel 47:1–9 (the river flowing from the threshold of the temple), Zechariah 14:8. All three converge in his person. John 2:19–21 has already identified Christ\'s body as the true temple; what flows from the temple in Ezekiel\'s vision flows from Christ in John\'s Gospel.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A direct fulfillment: the Evangelist\'s interpretive gloss — "by this he meant the Spirit" — identifies the living water of v.38 with the promised Spirit and ties its giving to the glorification of Christ (crucifixion, resurrection, ascension). Joel 2:28–29 promised that God would pour out the Spirit on all flesh; Ezekiel 36:26–27 promised a new heart and God\'s Spirit within his people. Both are fulfilled at Pentecost, but Pentecost depends on the cross: the Spirit cannot be given until Christ is glorified. Every drop of the Spirit\'s ministry flows from the accomplished work of the one who cried out at the feast.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A shadow: "Surely this man is the Prophet" — the identification with the prophet of Deuteronomy 18:15 ("the LORD your God will raise up for you a prophet like me from among your own people; you must listen to him") is the crowd\'s correct but partial recognition. Christ is the prophet like Moses — the one who speaks God\'s words directly — but the title understates the reality: he is not merely a prophet but the one to whom all the prophets testified (5:39).</p>',
    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: "He is the Messiah" — the higher identification is correct; the immediately following objection is based on ignorance of Jesus\'s birth. "How can the Messiah come from Galilee?" — the question expects a negative answer, but the Evangelist\'s irony is that it has a positive one: the Messiah does not come from Galilee. He comes from Bethlehem (born) and from the Father (origin). The objection is an unwitting argument for the identification the objectors mean to refute.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "Does not Scripture say that the Messiah will come from David\'s descendants and from Bethlehem?" — Micah 5:2 ("But you, Bethlehem Ephrathah... out of you will come for me one who will be ruler over Israel") and 2 Samuel 7:12–13 (the Davidic covenant) are the texts cited. The Evangelist intends the reader to recognize that Jesus fulfills both: he is born in Bethlehem (the birth narrative the Evangelist does not recount but assumes), and he is from David\'s line. The crowd\'s scriptural citation is the strongest argument for the identification they are trying to avoid.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A revelation of God: the division among the people because of Jesus fulfills Isaiah 8:14–15 — the LORD himself as a "stone that causes people to stumble and a rock that makes them fall." Luke 2:34 (Simeon\'s prophecy: "this child is destined to cause the falling and rising of many in Israel") is the explicit application. The Messiah\'s presence does not unify but divides — not because division is his purpose but because the light that reveals also separates those who come to it from those who flee it.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A revelation of God: again no one lays a hand on him — the divine protection of v.30 holds. The pattern is consistent throughout chapter 7: intent to arrest, divine prevention, no explanation given except the hour not yet come. The Evangelist does not dramatize the miraculous protection; he simply records the outcome. Christ\'s life is shielded by the same divine sovereignty that will eventually permit the cross.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: the failure of the temple guards to bring Jesus in begins the most remarkable exchange in the chapter. Their empty-handed return to the chief priests and Pharisees sets up the testimony of v.46. The institutional machinery of opposition has been sent out and returned without its object — a quiet demonstration that Jesus operates outside the control of those who claim authority over Israel\'s sacred space.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A fulfillment: "No one ever spoke the way this man does" — the guards\' testimony is the inadvertent fulfillment of Isaiah 50:4: "The Sovereign LORD has given me a well-instructed tongue... he wakens my ear to listen like one being taught." The Servant\'s speech is divinely given and irresistibly compelling; the guards sent to arrest Jesus are instead arrested by his words. The testimony comes from the least likely source — those whose assignment was suppression — which gives it maximum force.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A revelation of God: "You mean he has deceived you also?" — the Pharisees\' retort frames Christ\'s teaching as seduction rather than revelation. Jeremiah 5:31 describes a state where false prophets deceive and people love it; the charge is here inverted — the truthful prophet is accused of the deception that the religious establishment is practicing. The Evangelist\'s irony cuts deep: those accusing Christ of deception are the ones suppressing the truth about him.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A revelation of God: "Have any of the rulers or of the Pharisees believed in him?" — the argument from authority is the final resort of those who have no better response to the guards\' testimony. The Evangelist will shortly show (19:38–39; 12:42) that the rulers\' unbelief is not unanimous; Nicodemus (present in this very meeting) and Joseph of Arimathea are exceptions. The appeal to authority is both factually unstable and theologically irrelevant to the question of whether Jesus is who he claims to be.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A revelation of God: "this mob that knows nothing of the law — there is a curse on them" — the Pharisees invoke Deuteronomy 28:15–20 (the covenant curses on those who do not obey) against those responding to Christ. The irony is precise: the curse of the law falls on the lawbreaker; the crowd responding to Jesus is not breaking Torah but fulfilling it by recognizing the one to whom Torah pointed. The Pharisees wield the curse against the very people to whom the Messiah is being revealed.</p>',
    "50": '<p>A revelation of God: Nicodemus appears — the same Pharisee who came to Jesus by night in chapter 3, who is one of their own number, who has not yet fully declared himself. His presence in the Sanhedrin at this moment is itself a form of witness: even in the council of those determined to arrest Jesus, there is one who has heard him speak and cannot pretend he does not exist. The trajectory of Nicodemus will reach its completion at the burial (19:39), where the night-visitor becomes the one who anoints Christ\'s body.</p>',
    "51": '<p>A revelation of God: Nicodemus\'s procedural intervention — "Does our law condemn a man without first hearing him?" — invokes Deuteronomy 19:15–17 (due process requiring witnesses to be heard). It is a limited defense, but it is a defense. The Evangelist shows that Christ\'s presence has created a witness even within the institution most committed to silencing him. The law that the Pharisees invoke against Jesus is here invoked to ensure he receives a hearing — a small but theologically significant moment of the law functioning as it was designed.</p>',
    "52": '<p>A shadow: the reply to Nicodemus — "are you from Galilee too? Look into it, and you will find that a prophet does not come out of Galilee" — is factually wrong on both counts. A prophet did come out of Galilee: Jonah son of Amittai was from Gath-hepher in Galilee (2 Kgs 14:25). And Jesus was not from Galilee in the sense they mean: he was born in Bethlehem. The authorities\' dismissal rests on a double error. Their confident citation of precedent is precisely what fails them — they know the letter of the tradition without understanding what it points to.</p>',
    "53": '<p>A revelation of God: the chapter ends with dispersal — everyone going home, the division unresolved, no arrest made, no verdict reached. The Evangelist closes the feast sequence without resolution because the resolution is the cross. Chapter 7 has staged the contest between Christ and the religious establishment in its public, institutional form; chapters 18–19 will bring it to its conclusion. The departure of each person to his own house is a figure for the deeper isolation of those who encounter Christ and do not receive him — they return to their own, to themselves, rather than to the one who is the truth.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'john')
    merge_comm(existing, JOHN)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'john', existing)
    print('John 7 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
